            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 17,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 1.0,
                "text": "BACKGROUND"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 18,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "prefix": 1.1,
                "text": "This document sets out the procedures to be followed by all staff who produce information about research studies provided to potential participants, prior to the participant consenting to participate in the study."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 19,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 2.0,
                "text": "PURPOSE"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 20,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf To ensure all Mid Essex Hospital Services NHS Trust (MEHT) sponsored studies have appropriately designed patient information documents such as patient information sheets and consent forms to assist staff in consenting patients."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 21,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf To ensure that the patient information documents including trial advertisement meet all ethical and legal requirements."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 22,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 3.0,
                "text": "APPLICABLE TO"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 23,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "prefix": 3.1,
                "text": "All relevant Trust employees (including those with an honorary research contract or letter of access) involved with clinical research sponsored by MEHT including, Chief Investigators (CI), Principal Investigators (PI), Consultants, Co-investigators, Research Fellows, Clinical Trial Pharmacists, Research Managers, Statisticians, Research Nurses, Research Midwives, Allied Health Professionals, Trial Coordinators & Data Managers."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 24,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 4.0,
                "text": "RESPONSIBILITIES"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 25,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "prefix": 4.1,
                "text": "The Chief Investigator (CI) or delegated individual (DI) must ensure that all patients are fully informed about the trial before they provide consent, therefore, they should ensure that the patient information documents contain all the relevant information regarding the trial and are comprehensible to potential trial participants."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 26,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "prefix": 4.2,
                "text": "The research personnel delegated the responsibility of obtaining informed consent on the study delegation log must ensure that the patient information sheets are used to assist in the consenting procedure in line with Good Clinical Practice (GCP) guidance. They must also ensure that the correct versions of the patient information documents are available and that they have all necessary approvals before being put into practice."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 27,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "prefix": 4.3,
                "text": "The Health Research Authority (HRA) and Research Ethics Committee (REC) are responsible for ensuring that the patient information documents provided by the CI are sufficient for the trial and that the information provided is clear and easy to understand. They are also responsible for considering if trial participants require re- consenting as a result of any amendments to the patient information."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 28,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "prefix": 4.4,
                "text": "The R&D department is responsible for ensuring that the patient information documents have the necessary regulatory approvals in place before implementation of these documents is granted."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 29,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 5.0,
                "text": "PROCEDURE"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 30,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.0.1 Patient information documents should inform the patient about the nature and conduct of the trial, examples of patient information documents include informed consent forms, patient information sheets, questionnaires, GP letters, advertisements etc."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 31,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.0.2 The patient information documents should only be developed once the protocol has been finalised and agreed by appropriate team members and associated departments such as R&D, statistics, pharmacy, imaging etc. (see gSOP-14)."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 32,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.0.3 All of the patient information documents must be clearly version and date controlled to ensure that the correct versions are used when amendments occur as detailed"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 33,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.0.4 A separate patient information sheet and informed consent form must be provided in cases where there is more than one element to the study, for example, tissue biomarker or PET scan sub study."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 34,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.0.5 When designing any documents for a study that will be used by the patient it is important to ensure that they are:"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 35,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf Clear"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 36,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf Concise"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 37,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf Non-technical, but provide appropriate amount of detail"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 38,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf Sensitive"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 39,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf Invitational rather than persuasive"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 40,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "\u25cf Version and date controlled"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 41,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 5.1,
                "text": "Development of Patient Information"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 42,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "5.1.1 Patient Information Sheet"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 43,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "The patient information sheets are a detailed guide to the study written in layman terms with information regarding participating in the trial. They are a vital part of the informed consent procedure as they are used to help the patient determine if the study interests them and if they would like to receive further information from a doctor regarding participation."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 44,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.2 Details regarding the content and examples of wording can be found on the National Research Ethics Service (NRES)/ Health Research Authority (HRA) website under \u2013 Consent and Participant Information Sheet Preparation Guidance."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 45,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.3 Patent information sheets must explain exactly what the study entails for the participant and also what will happen with any data collected. It is important to ensure that if any patient details or information is to be transferred outside of the European Union that a statement such as the following should be included,"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 46,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "5.1.4 \u2018Some non-EEA countries, including the U.S. may not offer the same levels of privacy protection that you have in the UK.'"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 47,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "5.1.5 Consent Form"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 48,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "The consent form documents that informed consent has been taken, after having been informed of all aspects of the trial that are relevant to the subject's decision to participate. 5.1.6 Informed consent is documented by means of a written, signed and dated informed consent form."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 49,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.7 Please refer to gSOP-04 for further information on Obtaining and Documenting Informed Consent in Research at MEHT."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 50,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.8 For details about the content and examples of wording in consent form, please refer to the HRA website. \u2013  Consent and Participant Information Sheet Preparation Guidance."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 51,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "5.1.9 GP Letters"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 52,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "The GP letters should inform the doctor of their patient's participation in the trial and provide contact details of the team responsible for the patient whilst they are participating in the trial. It may be helpful to attach the PIS or summary for the GP's information."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 53,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "5.1.10 Questionnaires"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 54,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "It is important where possible to use questionnaires that have been validated as appropriate tools to collect the required information, for example, the quality of life tool EORTC QLQ-C30."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 55,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.11 These questionnaires should be discussed fully with the study statistician as they will be a vital tool in collecting the required data for the study."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 56,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.12 It is important to consider how these documents will be completed, i.e. in conjunction with either a doctor or nurse or if they will be sent in the post to be completed. The method for completion of the questionnaires should be documented in the protocol."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 57,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "5.1.13 Advertisement"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 58,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "If a trial uses any advertisement for patient recruitment, they should contain a brief description of the purpose of the trial and the type of participant that would be recruited."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 59,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.14 When designing the advertisements recruitment measures taken should be appropriate and not coercive i.e. advertisements are invitational rather than persuasive."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 60,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.1.15 They should also contain appropriate contact details for further information."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 61,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 5.2,
                "text": "Patient Information Ongoing Review, Amendments and Re-consenting Requirements"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 62,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.2.1 The study should be continually reviewed by the CI or the delegated personnel (DI) and the relevant oversight committees (Please see gSOP-10) to ensure that patient safety and the risk/benefit ratio is maintained."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 63,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.2.2 Any patient information document amendments should be produced in conjunction with the appropriate research team members, study statistician and be reviewed by R&D before being submitted as an amendment (please see gSOP-08)."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 64,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.2.3 It is important when amending these documents to consider whether re-consenting patients is required as a result of changes in procedures or updates to safety information, however, this should also be reviewed by both the HRA and REC."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 65,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.2.4 All document versions should be kept in the TMF although it is important to ensure that superseded versions are clearly marked (gSOP-05)."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 66,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "5.2.5 It is important that a version control log is maintained detailing a summary of the amendment and when that version received the necessary approvals."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 67,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 7.0,
                "text": "EQUALITY IMPACT ASSESSMENT"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 68,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "prefix": 7.1,
                "text": "Mid Essex Hospital Services NHS Trust is committed to the provision of a service that is fair, accessible and meets the needs of all individuals. (Refer to Appendix 2)"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 69,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Appendix 1: Definitions"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 70,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Chief Investigator (CI) -  The person who takes overall responsibility for the design, conduct and reporting of a study if it is at one site; or if the study involves researchers at more than one site, the person who takes primary responsibility for the design conduct and reporting of the study whether or not that person is an Investigator at any particular site."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 71,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Clinical Trial Investigational Medicinal Products (CTIMP) - Any investigation in human subjects intended to discover or verify the clinical, pharmacological and / or other pharmacodynamic effects of one or more investigational medicinal product(s), and/or to identify any adverse reactions to one or more investigational medicinal product(s) and / or to study absorption, distribution, metabolism and excretion of one or more investigational medicinal product(s) with the object of ascertaining its (their) safety and / or efficacy."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 72,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Delegated Individual (DI) \u2013 an individual delegated by the PI to carry out tasks"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 73,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "prefix": 1.0,
                "text": "Good Clinical Practice (GCP) \u2013 The principles of GCP in clinical trials as set down in articles 2-5 of the GCP Directive and implemented in the UK by Schedule  of the Medicines for Human Use (Clinical Trials) regulations 2004 (S.I.2004/1031) as amended by the S.I.2006/1928."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 74,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "GCP is a set of internationally recognised ethical and scientific quality requirements which must be observed for designing, conducting, recording and reporting clinical trials that involve the participation of human subjects."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 75,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Health Research  Authority (HRA) - The primary role of the HRA is to protect and promote the interests of patients and the public in health research and to streamline the regulation of research."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 76,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Investigational Medicinal Products (IMP) - means a pharmaceutical form of an active substance or placebo being tested, or used as a reference in a clinical trial. This includes a medicinal product which has a marketing authorisation but is, for the purposes of the trial -"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 77,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "(a) used or assembled (formulated or packaged) in a way different from the form of the product authorised under the authorisation,"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 78,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "(b) used for an indication not included in the summary of product characteristics under the authorisation for that product, or"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 79,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "(c) used to gain further information about the form of that product as authorised under the authorisation"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 80,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Principal Investigator (PI) - The leader responsible for a team of individuals conducting a study at a (participating) site."
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 81,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 1,
                "text": "Research Ethics Committee (REC) - RECs review research proposals and give an opinion about whether the research is ethical. They also look at issues such as the participant involvement in the research. The committees are entirely independent of research sponsors (the organisations responsible for the management and conduct of the research), funders and the researchers themselves. This enables them to put participants"
            }
        },
        {
            "type": "ListItem",
            "sequence_num": 82,
            "data": {
                "is_heading": 0,
                "text": "at the centre of their review."
            }
        },
